&lt;div class="post-text" itemprop="text"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As always with these questions, the JLS holds the answer. In this case &lt;a href="http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.26.2"&gt;Â§15.26.2 Compound Assignment Operators&lt;/a&gt;. An extract:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;A compound assignment expression of the form &lt;code&gt;E1Â op=Â E2&lt;/code&gt; is equivalent to &lt;code&gt;E1Â =Â (T)((E1)Â opÂ (E2))&lt;/code&gt;, where &lt;code&gt;T&lt;/code&gt; is the type of &lt;code&gt;E1&lt;/code&gt;, except that &lt;code&gt;E1&lt;/code&gt; is evaluated only once.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;An example cited from &lt;a href="http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.26.2"&gt;Â§15.26.2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;[...] the following code is correct:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;short x = 3;
x += 4.6;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

  &lt;p&gt;and results in x having the value 7 because it is equivalent to:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;short x = 3;
x = (short)(x + 4.6);
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In other words, your assumption is correct.&lt;/p&gt;
