&lt;p&gt;There are several PHP bugs about it:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=45346" rel="noreferrer"&gt;http://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=45346&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=51635" rel="noreferrer"&gt;http://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=51635&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=46758" rel="noreferrer"&gt;http://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=46758&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The same things happens here:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;$obj-&amp;gt;{0} = "hello";
$arr = (array)$obj;
echo $arr[0];
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It happens because the "0" is used as string array key, whereas $arr[0] searches for the integer array key. It is documented in the PHP documentation simply by stating: &lt;em&gt;integer properties are unaccessible&lt;/em&gt; (&lt;a href="http://docs.php.net/manual/en/language.types.array.php#language.types.array.casting" rel="noreferrer"&gt;link&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

